SIMPLE: finesse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Finesse
<hw>Fi`nesse"</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr.
<ets>fin</ets> fine. See <er>Fine</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Subtilty of contrivance to gain a point; artifice;
stratagem.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is the artificialest piece of <qex>finesse</qex> to persuade
men into slavery.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Whist Playing)</fld> <def>The act of finessing. See
<er>Finesse</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Finesse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Finesse
<hw>Fi*nesse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Finessed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Finessing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To use
artifice or stratagem.</def> <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Whist Playing)</fld> <def>To attempt, when second
or third player, to make a lower card answer the purpose of a higher,
when an intermediate card is out, risking the chance of its being held
by the opponent yet to play.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Finestill</ent>⟦br⟧
